Remarks
. Oar-shaped chaetae in dorsal bundles usually begin to appear in VII or VIII, and they completely replace bifid crotchets from VIIIâ€“XI on. Therefore, some 'transitional' chaetal bundles in VIIâ€“X have both bifid and oar-shaped chaetae, and occasionally their intermediates (
Figs. 13Gâ€“I
), in addition to hair chaetae. Replacement of bifid chaetae by oar-shaped chaetae proceeds from medial to lateral in each chaetal bundle. Paired testes were observed in V and VI in all mature specimens examined. Because segment V had no efferent duct, the testes of this segment are thought to be functionless. Large penes and glandular cap cells on penial chaetophores found in the present specimens agree well with earlier descriptions of this species (
Kowalewski 1914
; 
Ohtaka & Usman, 1997
).
